<TEXT>
political action committees financed by labor 
unions teachers and other interests are pouring huge chunks of 
money into legislative races in about a dozen states that are 
battlegrounds for congressional redistricting 
we are under siege like i have never seen said pennsylvania 
senate president robert jubelirer he and other republicans are 
trying to fend off a democratic offensive to take over the states 
upper chamber 
the stakes are high in pennsylvania because state democrats 
should they pick up three seats and wrest the senate from gop 
control could have absolute control in redrawing the states 
congressional districts next year democratic gov robert casey is 
likely to roll to reelection and the pennsylvania house is 
expected to stay democratic 
similar shootouts are occurring in other states that stand to 
win or lose when 19 us house seats change hands in 1991 because 
of population shifts detected by the 1990 census 
eight states are expected to gain house seats and 13 to lose 
seats in addition political boundaries within every state will be 
redrawn regardless of whether the states win or lose seats 
the national republican and democratic parties have invested 
heavily in the states affected the most by redistricting and each 
side is getting reinforcements from its allies with labor backing 
the democrats and business and conservative interests aiding the 
gop 
state legislative races and gubernatorial contests are crucial 
because those elected officials will control the highly political 
process of redrawing boundary lines for congressional and state 
legislative districts 
therefore tuesdays elections will determine whether democrats 
or republicans get to draw the districts or whether the two parties 
split the responsibility by slicing up districts in either liberal 
or conservative precincts politicians can help the election 
chances of either a republican or democrat 
legisatures draw up the lines governors are power brokers in 
the process too because a governor of one party affiliation a 
republican for instance could veto a plan drawn up by a 
democratic legislature 
most of the 19 house seats expected to shift will move from the 
democratictilting northeast and midwest to the more conservative 
south and west 
california texas and florida the big prizes on everyones 
list because they stand to gain as many as 14 congressional seats 
next year have attracted huge contributions from out of state 
democrats in illinois michigan pennsylvania and ohio which 
each stand to lose two congressional seats are luring hefty 
contributions as well 
reapportionment has been on everybodys mind for a very long 
time in the labor movement said janice lachance of the american 
federation of government employees 
tom heoffler of the national republican congressional committee 
said it is crucial for the gop to hold its ground to keep the 
democrats from taking total control in many states 
were looking at a situation here where its vital for us to 
hang on to what we have just to be in a divided or split 
position he said 
tim dickson executive director of the democratic national 
committees redistricting arm noted that efforts are just as 
important in states that stand to lose house seats 
its like musical chairs the musics going to stop when this 
legislative session ends and somebodys not going to have a 
seat dickson said 
democratic priorities in addition to capturing the pennsylvania 
senate include trying to reverse narrow gop majorities in the 
senates of michigan indiana ohio and new york 
republicans are trying to oust democrats to gain control in the 
senates of florida and illinois 
florida is an especially important redistricting battleground 
because it also has a close governors race in california and 
texas the gubernatorial races are attracting the most attention 
because both have legislatures handily controlled by democrats 
other legislative showdown states although not necessarily key 
in the congressional redistricting changes are arizona where 
republicans hold a fourseat majority in the senate colorado 
where democrats hope to make a stab at the gops 13seat house 
margin idaho where the gop holds a fourseat edge in the senate 
washington where republicans have a oneseat advantage in the 
senate and oregon where democrats have just four house seats over 
the republicans 
in state legislatures that share redistricting powers with 
governors democrats had a big edge going into the election they 
control both chambers in 29 states while republicans hold a lock 
on the statehouse in only four 
overall there are more than 6100 legislative seats at stake 
nationwide on tuesday 
