<TEXT>
youngsters in arizona dont have to wait until 
theyre 18 to vote they can go to the polls in kindergarten 
the kids voting program designed to improve the way 
americans vote believes in starting young 
its thrilling because it lets kids vote on things adults 
do says 9yearold stephanie schwartz who adds that shell 
probably vote for the rest of her life 
alyssa martin 16 said participating in the program has made 
her more aware of political issues 
now i read the newspaper about the candidates and i want to 
know more she said 
kids voting began in 1988 as a pilot program taking in parts of 
six school districts 30000 children voted 
two years later the program has grown to include about 200 
school districts around the state more than 600000 youngsters are 
eligible to vote 
voting booths for children in grades kindergarten through 12 
will be set up at 1797 of the states nearly 2000 precincts for 
tuesdays general election 
pupils vote with a special ballot in booths alongside the 
regular voting booths at adult polling places the results which 
will be tabulated by a private computer company are expected to be 
available on wednesday 
marilyn hawker kids voting president and executive director 
said voter turnout in the 65 precincts in which children voted two 
years ago was 3 percent higher than state and county election 
turnouts she expects the program to increase voter turnout 
throughout the state this year by 5 percent 
laurie delaney a social studies teacher in mesa said some of 
her students said their parents registered to vote for the first 
time after the students became involved in kids voting 
the ballot issues that the youngsters will vote on include 
statewide offices propositions and legislative races plus some 
studentrelated issues not on the adult ballots such as linking 
driving privileges with regular school attendance 
in another effort to deal with civic illiteracy millions of 
junior and senior high school students and their parents voted in a 
nationwide mock election last thursday they cast ballots on 
individual state races as well as on general issues involving drugs 
and defense 
the idea for arizonas kids voting program came during a 1987 
fishing trip to costa rica where the voter turnout reaches over 90 
percent 
bob evans chairman of the kids voting board of directors and 
several others made a forced airplane landing in a village in the 
small central american country they met a taxi driver who told 
them of a childhood of voting alongside his parents in simulated 
elections 
evans hopes the idea will overcome voter apathy 
according to federal statistics 50 percent of eligible citizens 
dont vote in presidential elections and 70 percent dont vote in 
local elections arizona ranked 36th in the nation in voter turnout 
in 1988 
voter apathy is the worst disease that we have within our own 
particular democracy and it has been a creeping disease over the 
last 75 years evans said were hardly a government by the 
people any more because there are so few people participating 
the program already has affected the governors race between 
democrat terry goddard and republican fife symington both of whom 
participated in a televised kids voting program 
goddard later issued a statement to clarify his position after 
learning he appeared to be losing ground among the youthful voters 
over his comments on yearround school one of the studentrelated 
issues on which kids voting participants will cast ballots 
goddard said during the broadcast that the united states might 
have to adopt an intensive program such as that used in japanese 
schools in his later statement he said he didnt advocate keeping 
students in school yearround but would like to see the facilities 
have greater use 
the kids voting program is expected to cost about 600000 with 
95 percent of the funding coming from private corporations 
primarily arizona public service co ms hawker said 
