<TEXT>
harry weinberg a reclusive millionaire who made 
a fortune in baltimore and hawaii has died at age 82 leaving a 
900 million charitable trust one of the biggest in the country 
weinberg died sunday at the queens medical center after an 
eightyear battle with bone cancer 
he earned millions in real estate municipal transit companies 
and other ventures in a familiar american success story 
last month forbes magazine estimated weinbergs worth at 950 
million ranking him 70th on its list of the 400 richest americans 
his family immigrated to baltimore in 1912 from what was the 
austrohungarian empire weinberg quit school at 12 worked in his 
fathers auto shop sold newspapers on the side and eventually 
parlayed a series of remarkably successful business deals into 
enormous wealth 
he began acquiring land during the depression buying 47 
properties in downtown baltimore alone 
a millionaire by the end of world war ii weinberg began buying 
moneylosing private transit companies in baltimore scranton pa 
dallas new york and honolulu he later sold them at enormous 
profit 
after visiting honolulu in the early 1950s he recognized that 
jet travel would make hawaiis tropical islands accessible to 
middleclass tourists 
he acquired oahu and maui properties that form the bulk of the 
estate and are now worth hundreds of millions of dollars in one of 
the nations hottest real estate markets 
weinberg moved from baltimore to honolulu in 1968 but had 
already set up a baltimorebased foundation for the poor that bears 
his name and that of his wife who died in 1989 
the harry and jeanette weinberg foundation which will receive 
most of his estate will be among the nations 12 largest worth 
at least 900 million and obligated to spend as much as 45 million 
a year said shale d stiller attorney for the foundation 
it really is an unbelievable task said stiller its an 
incredible amount of money to give away 
weinberg left nothing to his son morton said stiller 
by all accounts harry weinberg was a man with little interest 
in anything but business although he accumulated enormous wealth 
he never bothered with the trappings his offices were drab his 
car was 10 or 15 years old his clothes came off the rack and he 
hated publicity 
he didnt play golf he didnt play tennis said morton 
weinberg who lives near los angeles his business was his life 
he didnt waste his time doing other things 
criticized as a callous landlord who neglected his properties 
weinberg revealed a softer side after learning he had cancer he 
announced he would give all his money away and developed a special 
concern for the elderly 
on his final 1989 pilgrimage to israel a nation whose birth he 
witnessed in 1948 he asked to visit several of tel avivs nursing 
homes 
it was a humid summer day weinberg surprised the nursing homes 
did not have air conditioning wrote a check for 1 million to pay 
to cool every nursing home in israel 
before his death he stipulated that the foundation give at 
least 25 percent of its yearly donations to predominately jewish 
charities 
besides his son weinberg is survived by three brothers one 
sister and four grandchildren 
</TEXT>
