<TEXT>
no one could crow better than mary martin 
sure there were other peter pans sandy duncan for example 
and even gymnast cathy rigby who opens in a revival of the musical 
on broadway next month 
but martins cockadoodle was special it started in the back 
of her throat built slowly almost impishly and then roared out 
at the audience 
martin would crow anywhere tony award shows banquets high 
school auditoriums television talk shows the middle of a busy 
manhattan street even newspaper interviews just ask and she 
obliged 
thats why audiences liked her she was downtoearth texas 
friendly martin would dazzle them with her sweet pure singing 
voice and make them laugh with her tomboyish charm and sense of 
fun 
there are more wonderful photographic memories of martin than 
any other broadway star conjure up the following martin sitting 
on a trunk innocently singing my heart belongs to daddy in 
leave it to me or draped over a chair in one touch of 
venus doing a sexy witty rendition of thats him or washing 
her hair on stage in south pacific or flying high in peter 
pan or holding a guitar and singing to all those little children 
in the sound of music the memories dont stop 
and she never seemed to grow old her television taping of 
peter pan the one preserved forever on videotape was done in 
1960 when she was 47 youd never know it the woman seemed 
eternally youthful 
theater critics loved martin as much as theatergoers did they 
would fall over their adjectives trying to find new ways to write 
valentines to her 
harold clurman reviewing south pacific burbled when mary 
martin tells us with radiant good nature im in love im in 
love im in love with a wonderful guy one doesnt murmur who 
cares but congratulations congratulations congratulations to 
you both 
even if the critics didnt like the show she was in most of 
their notices were unabashed love letters wrote walter kerr in the 
new york herald tribune after martin opened in jennie a 
somber unhappy musical imagine having mary martin play an 
entire show with the corners of her mouth down its like using the 
moon not to make love by miss martin forever but not as 
jennie 
martin was a broadway star one of the few performers whose name 
meant something special in the theater she never much liked her 
movies or making them too impersonal 
no time to think its shoot boom if you dont get it right 
the first time do it again she said of her hollywood days 
ironically it was television that cemented her theater career 
making her even bigger box office on broadway besides peter 
pan she starred in a series of classy television specials 
among them a 1953 50th anniversary salute to the ford motor co 
that costarred ethel merman a 90minute program with noel coward 
called together with music and a television version of annie 
get your gun costarring john raitt these programs brought her 
an enormous audience that would turn into her staunchest theater 
supporters 
i hope as i go out im crowing martin once said when 
that time comes im ready for it 
she may have been ready but we werent thank goodness for the 
rca original cast recording of peter pan and the invaluable 
videotape just released on cassette last september those sounds 
and images wont fade 
