<TEXT>
a shinto shrine in southern japan was damaged by a 
fire early today and police believe the attack was part of a 
terrorist campaign by leftist radicals who hope to disrupt next 
weeks coronation 
officials on the island of okinawa said no one was in the shrine 
at the time of the fire which was quickly extinguished there were 
no injuries 
the attack came four days after two explosions rocked a police 
dormitory in tokyo killing one policeman and injuring six other 
people 
if radicals were involved police say the shrine blaze would be 
the 62nd guerrilla incident this year and the 10th since oct 1 
compared with only 27 incidents in all of 1989 
shinto japans indigenous religion is closely associated with 
the monarchy and leftists view the emperor as a symbol of japans 
militarist past 
many critics contend that the nov 12 governmentsponsored 
coronation ceremony which has strong religious underpinnings is a 
violation of the constitutional separation of church and state 
the attacks by radicals have heightened fears that police 
efforts to guard the coronation may not be enough to keep radicals 
from causing trouble a possibility officials grudgingly 
acknowledge 
police in tokyo are mounting their largest security operation 
ever with 26000 officers more than half the tokyo metropolitan 
police department already deployed on coronationrelated 
assignments 
at least another 6000 reinforcements will be brought in from 
other police forces over the next week bringing the total to 
32000 by coronation day 
if they were to attempt an attack on the palace we could stop 
them a highranking police official recently told reporters 
but when they disguise themselves as regular citizens they are 
very hard to uncover 
police today raided several buildings used by japans two 
largest radical groups the 5000member chukakuha or middle core 
faction and the kakurokyo or revolutionary workers association 
no arrests were reported 
about 70 officers many clad in full riot gear forced their way 
into the kakurokyos tokyo headquarters a radical who was in the 
building said the raid lasted about two hours 
news reports said police believe a faction within the kakurokyo 
which has about 800 members is responsible for thursdays 
dormitory blasts 
police would make no official comment on those reports they 
said todays raid was part of an investigation into a separate 
incident last month 
</TEXT>
