<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to hear the 
appeal of a texas woman who says she lost parental rights over her 
young daughter because the free legal help she got was inadequate 
the justices over one dissenting vote turned down a request to 
use the case to decide whether poor people may challenge the 
competency of their courtappointed lawyers when states seek to 
take away their children 
justice harry a blackmun voted to hear arguments in the case 
but four votes are needed to grant such review 
in a series of decisions the high court has ruled that poor 
criminal defendants facing serious charges have a constitutional 
right to free and effective legal help 
and in a key 1984 ruling the court said a defendants 
conviction may be overturned if he or she can prove a 
courtappointed lawyers deficiency calls into question the 
results reliability 
the justices in 1981 said poor people facing termination of 
parental rights may have a dueprocess right to free legal help 
but the court never has said that such help must meet any specific 
standard of effectiveness 
nicolosa barnes was stripped of parental rights to her daughter 
christina in 1987 by the dallas county child welfare unit of the 
texas department of human resources 
court records indicate that christina then 5 years old was 
suffering from malnutrition 
doctors said the child was frail and listless and had bleeding 
sores in her mouth one doctor said it appeared the child had been 
starved for two weeks 
mrs barnes husband harold also was stripped of parental 
rights to christina he did not appeal the barneses also have 
three sons according to court documents 
in the appeal acted on today mrs barnes said her 
courtappointed lawyer called no witnesses in the parentalrights 
termination hearing made no prehearing investigation and failed to 
object to harmful and inadmissible evidence 
when an indigent is entitled to appointment of counsel when 
the permanent deprivation of ones child is at stake that counsel 
must be competent or the judgment should be set aside the appeal 
contended 
the texas supreme court rejected mrs barnes appeal last march 
the case is barnes vs dallas county child welfare unit 
905156 
</TEXT>
