<DOCNO> AP901105-0058 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that barred employee benefit plans from discriminating against 
workers who are disabled later in their careers 
the court without comment rejected arguments by ohio officials 
that younger workers forced to retire because of disabilities are 
entitled to greater benefits 
the dispute between the ohio public employees retirement system 
and retired speech pathologist june betts led to a ruling by the 
justices last year in favor of the state officials 
the high court in 1989 said a state law permitting reduced 
benefits for ms betts did not violate a federal law banning age 
bias in employment unless she can prove intentional 
discrimination in some nonfringe benefit aspect of the 
employment relation 
the ruling appeared to say workers charging age bias must prove 
that reduced fringe benefits were aimed for example at 
discouraging older workers from applying for jobs or were intended 
to force them to quit 
but the 1989 decision was not the end of ms betts case 
the high court sent it back to the 6th us circuit court of 
appeals to determine whether she was forced to retire and 
therefore may not be penalized with reduced benefits 
the appeals court ruled her retirement was involuntary 
ms betts was a speech pathologist for the hamilton county 
mental retardation department when her ability to work 
deteriorated because of health problems she was given a choice by 
the state in 1985 of taking unpaid medical leave or retirement with 
a standard pension 
she was barred from receiving more generous disability 
retirement benefits because she was 61 a provision of the state 
pension plan allows disability benefits only for those who worked 
for the state for at least five years and were under 60 when forced 
to quit 
ms betts pension was 15850 a month under the standard plan 
compared to 355 a month she would have received in disability 
retirement benefits 
the 6th circuit court reexamining the case after the 1989 high 
court ruling said ms betts was the victim of illegal age 
discrimination 
she was denied the choice of disability benefits which would 
have been available to her had she been one year younger the 
appeals court said employers may not force older workers 
involuntarily into less desirable retirement programs on the basis 
of age such coercive conduct constitutes involuntary retirement 
the case is public employees retirement system of ohio vs 
betts 90451 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

