<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
allowing prosecutors to punish businesses convicted of dealing in 
obscenity by seizing their property 
the court without comment rejected an adult bookstores 
challenge to an illinois antipornography law 
the justices recently boosted efforts to crack down on 
obscenity 
the court last year ruled in a case from indiana that states may 
use antiracketeering laws in the drive against adult bookstores 
and other businesses that sell or display sexually explicit 
material 
but the court said in that ruling that prosecutors may not use 
such tough crimefighting measures to shut down the businesses 
before trials are held to determine whether any of the material 
sold is obscene 
last month the court left intact the forced closing by federal 
officials of three adult bookstores and nine video rental shops in 
virginia a lower court ruled that seizing their property after 
they were convicted of racketeering and selling obscene material 
did not violate the bookstore owners freespeech rights 
in the case acted on today the 7th us circuit court of 
appeals upheld an illinois law challenged by sequoia books inc 
owner of the denmark ii bookstore in kendall county 
sequoia books was convicted of selling obscene materials 12 
times between january 1985 and september 1987 
an illinois law that took effect jan 1 1989 lets authorities 
seize property derived from or used to commit obscenity 
offenses any business convicted at least twice of obscenity 
violations is subject to forfeiting its property 
the 7th circuit court said the law may not be applied 
retroactively but said sequoias property may be seized for any 
obscenity violation from 1989 onward 
the bookstores owners said the law operates as a prior 
restraint on free expression 
fearing an obscenity conviction that could be economically 
devastating the owners said they are forced to engage in 
selfcensorship and stop selling adultoriented material that may 
not be obscene 
the 7th circuit court rejected the argument noting that the 
illinois law is less sweeping than the seizure provisions of the 
federal antiracketeering law that has survived similar challenges 
a previous attempt by illinois officials to use a public 
nuisance law to shut down the denmark ii bookstore was declared 
unconstitutional by the illinois supreme court 
the state court said officials may not use public nuisance laws 
to shut down establishments that sell nonobscene works merely 
because some obscene material was sold there 
sexually explicit material often characterized as pornography 
is not necessarily obscene obscenity a legal term must be 
determined in a judicial proceeding 
sexually explicit material judged obscene enjoys no freespeech 
protection if the material is not found to be obscene it is 
protected by constitutional freespeech guarantees 
the case is sequoia books vs ingemunson 90454 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

