<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to use a 
california murder case to set new guidelines for federal court 
appeals by convicted defendants who say their rights were violated 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by state officials in 
the case of owen duane nunnemaker sentenced to life in prison for 
murdering his estranged wife in 1975 
the court is expected to announce a ruling by july 
nunnemaker shot his wife alice in her home in sebastopol he 
testified that he did not recall the shooting and did not intend to 
kill her 
at his trial nunnemakers lawyer objected to statements made by 
a state psychiatrist but did not claim the psychiatrist violated 
the defendants rights by questioning him without warning him of 
his right to remain silent and to have an attorney present 
some 10 years later nunnemaker began a new round of state court 
appeals arguing the psychiatrist violated his rights 
the appeals were unsuccessful culminating with the california 
supreme court denying him a hearing without comment 
nunnemaker then turned to the federal courts for help a federal 
judge ruled that the defendant was barred now from arguing the 
psychiatrist violated his rights because no such claim was made at 
his trial 
but the 9th us circuit court of appeals reversed the judges 
ruling in may and ordered the judge to conduct further hearings 
the appeals court said the state supreme courts failure to 
explain why it denied nunnemakers appeal opens the way for further 
federal court review such federal court appeals are called habeas 
corpus petitions postconviction challenges by defendants who say 
their rights were violated 
relying on a us supreme court ruling last year the 9th 
circuit court said where a state supreme court does not plainly 
state in its summary denial of an original habeas petition that its 
ruling rests on a state procedural bar federal review is not 
precluded 
the us supreme court in 1989 revived a chicago murderers 
challenge to his conviction the justices in that case said the 
defendant had lost a state court appeal on ambiguous grounds 
because the state court did not say clearly that it was relying on 
procedural grounds to foreclose any new federal court appeal 
the california attorney generals office said the 9th circuit 
court ruling will permit cynical manipulation of the 
postconviction remedies provided by the state and federal 
systems the state lawyers said hundreds of cases each year in 
california will be affected 
the case acted on today is ylst vs nunnemaker 9068 
</TEXT>
