<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that someone 
suing more than one defendant generally does not have to include 
all of them in the same lawsuit 
in a unanimous unsigned opinion the court revived a suit by a 
mississippi man stemming from his back surgery in 1986 
the patient billy j temple had a plate and screw device 
implanted in his lower spine the screws broke off inside his back 
the operation was performed by dr s henry larocca at st 
charles general hospital in new orleans the device was made by 
synthes ltd 
temple sued the manufacturer in federal court in louisiana he 
filed a separate negligence and malpractice suit against the doctor 
and hospital in louisiana state court 
a federal judge threw out the suit against synthes and the 
decision was upheld by the 5th us circuit court of appeals the 
federal courts said temple should have sued all three defendants 
together 
the supeme court today reversed those rulings 
the high court said it has long been the rule that it is not 
necessary for all joint tortfeasors defendants in personal injury 
cases to be named as defendants in a single lawsuit 
the court rejected arguments by synthes that a 1966 revised 
court rule changed that principle 
the justices said that while they encourage judicial economy 
and efficiency by suing all defendants together there is no 
evidence larocca and the hospital are indispensable to the case 
against synthes 
temples hometown was not available in court papers here 
the case is temple vs synthes 90295 
