<TEXT>
a federal judge today declined to set bail for 
joseph doherty the irish revoltionary who has been jailed in new 
york for more than seven years 
us district judge miriam g cedarbaum ruled that doherty would 
likely flee if his release were approved 
the evidence is overwhelming that petitioner if released 
would pose such a substantial risk of flight that no condition of 
bail could reasonably assure his surrender for deportation 
cedarbaum said in a 23page decision 
doherty 35 faces alife sentence in the united kingdom for the 
murder of a british officer killed in a gunfight between british 
troops and dohertys fourman ira unit 
he escaped from a prison in northern ireland in 1981 and came to 
the united states a year later he was arrested in new york in 1983 
and has been imprisoned in a manhattan jail since then 
doherty has never been charged with a crime in the united 
states hes been held without bail the entire time 
a call to his attorneys was not immediately returned today 
dohertys request for bail was made in the form of a writ of 
habeus corpus which claimed his constitutional right to due 
process was violated by his lengthy imprisonment 
he had sought release on bail while continuing efforts to fight 
deportation and gain political asylum in the united states 
while conceding that the length of his detention was extremely 
troubling the judge rejected the argument that dohertys 
constitutional rights were violated 
she noted that many of the constitutional protections given 
people accused of crimes did not apply to aliens in deportation 
proceedings 
she also ruled that the us government was not responsible for 
delaying his deportation proceedings to the contrary his own 
strategic maneuvers have caused significant delays cedarbaum 
said 
she said dohertys continued detention continues to serve the 
valid regulatory purpose of keeping him available for 
deportation 
cedarbaums ruling followed a hearing held over several days in 
september and october during which doherty testified that he was 
no longer a member of the ira 
he had promised the judge that he would abide by any conditions 
of bail and would willingly return to the united kingdom if he lost 
his bid for asylum 
the us government which opposed dohertys release called as 
a witness an expert on terrorism who testified that ira membership 
was a cradle to grave proposition 
the almost exclusively roman catholic ira is fighting to push 
the british out of protestantdominated northern ireland join it 
with the republic of ireland and set up an allireland socialist 
state 
