the recommendations said health secretary louis sullivan are 
also more specific than guidelines issued in 1980 and 1985 
the new ones include more positive advice oriented to the 
total diet with clear wording and specific numbers he said 
for example the 27page booklet of guidelines being distributed 
by the government says americans should get 30 percent or less of 
their calories from fat with only 10 percent of that from animal 
fat and tropical oils 
other guidelines 
eat two or three servings daily of meat poultry fish dry 
beans or eggs but no more than 6 ounces a day 
trim fat from meat remove the skin from poultry and have 
cooked dry beans and peas instead of meat occasionally 
have two or three servings of milk and dairy products daily a 
serving is one cup of milk or yogurt or about 1 ounces of cheese 
have three or more servings of vegetables daily eating 
darkgreen leafy and deepyellow vegetables dry beans and peas 
often also eat starchy vegetables such as potatoes and corn 
eat two or more servings of fruit such as one medium apple an 
orange or a banana daily 
use sugar and salt in moderation 
if you drink alcoholic beverages do so in moderation 
the guidelines define moderation in drinking alcoholic beverages 
as one drink per day for women and no more than two drinks a day 
for men one drink means 12 ounces of regular beer five ounces of 
wine or 15 ounces of distilled spirits 80 proof 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter said the new guidelines 
would influence the national school lunch program run by usda and 
the women infant and children program which provides food 
vouchers for food and nutritional information to poor pregnant 
women nursing mothers and their babies 
we reach a large segment of the public with our food 
programs said yeutter who released the guidelines at a press 
conference with sullivan 
as children begin to eat with the family usually at about 2 
years of age they should be encouraged to choose diets that are 
lower in fat and saturated fat and that provide the calories and 
nutrients they need for normal growth says the pamphlet 
whats revolutionary in the new recommendations says the 
american school food service association is that the government is 
applying the guidelines to children for the first time 
anne gennings president of the school food service association 
said schools across the country already offer a variety of food 
choices lower in fat sugar and sodium the report reinforces that 
effort she said 
but ellen haas executive director of public voice for food and 
health policy said the government could do more 
whats important now is not focusing on the guidelines 
themselves but concrete action plans for translating the 
guidelines she said advocating laws or regulations requiring 
schools to cut meals to no more than 30 percent fat for example 
the center for science in the public interest also was critical 
saying the guidelines were weak and devoid of the urgency that 
the situation deserves 
the governments mealymouthed advice can hardly be expected 
to spur the major overhaul in eating habits that most americans 
should make said jane hurley the nonprofit groups associate 
nutritionist 
food industry organizations however were supportive 
the salt institute is pleased that the revised dietary 
guidelines now encourage americans to use salt or sodium in 
moderation said the trade group which opposed the words 
avoid salt in the 1985 guidelines 
the american meat institute said the guidelines were a prudent 
road map to healthy delicious and varied diets that provide 
ample room for all foods from all food groups to be included in 
americans diets 
todays lean trimmed beef fits well into the kinds of diets 
being recommended said the national cattlemens association 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

