<TEXT>
the council of europe marking the 40th anniversary 
of its human rights charter declared monday that it wants the 
united states and the soviet union to join in some of its 
functions 
the council is the oldest postwar body promoting european 
cooperation on tuesday it is to admit hungary as its first member 
from the former communist bloc 
the 23nation council issued a statement at the end of a meeting 
monday saying it wanted to help coordinate human rights issues for 
the csce or conference on security and cooperation in europe that 
organization is a loosely defined body of 34 nations that has been 
a forum for talks between cold war enemies 
for this purpose it the council of europe should adjust its 
structures and working methods to enable all the states 
participating in the csce which are not council members including 
canada the ussr and the usa to take part in some of its 
intergovernmental and parliamentary activities in the human rights 
field on an equal footing the declaration said 
earlier monday italian foreign minister gianni de michelis 
opened the meeting by calling for the councils assembly to develop 
into a parliament bringing together the former communist bloc and 
the west including the united states 
a us official said washington wanted to work with the council 
of europe in aiding emerging eastern european democracies 
but the official richard schifter assistant secretary of 
state for human rights said the united states was unlikely to 
become a member of the council of europe 
joining the council of europe would mean that final judgments 
of us courts can be reviewed and set aside he said such a 
situation would require amending the constitution he added 
rather than deal with this aspect of it theres many things 
we can do together he said after mondays meeting 
the session brought together council ministers and observers 
from eastern europe the united states canada the soviet union 
and other states 
they discussed what role the council would have in the postcold 
war era 
the council of europe is hoping to emerge as a political 
counterpart to organizations like nato which has stressed military 
cooperation and the european community which has focused on 
economic cooperation 
in his speech de michelis suggested that the councils assembly 
become the parliament for the csce countries 
only by maintaining the bigger picture involving the north 
american democracy will it be possible to face the question of 
historic dimensions of the relations between europe and the soviet 
union he said 
however the united states has raised objections to the plan 
washington has traditionally been wary of the csce because of its 
unwieldly size and the fact that the us voice carries only as 
much weight as that of the other csce participants 
the council of europes secretarygeneral catherine lalumiere 
said many speakers monday suggested using the councils european 
human rights convention as the basis for humanrights accords 
regulating the postcold war order 
it is essential to start building the europe of the future on 
a sound basis she said 
the convention is the bestknown of the 130 treaties signed by 
council of europe members 
it is unique in allowing individuals to sue their governments in 
an international court whose decisions are binding 
lalumiere said other conclusions reached monday included the 
need to reduce the backlog of such humanrights cases there was 
also a need to give fresh impulse to the european social charter 
which focuses on social and economic rights she said 
the council of europe includes austria belgium britain 
cyprus denmark finland france germany greece iceland 
ireland italy liechtenstein luxembourg malta netherlands 
norway portugal san marino spain sweden switzerland and 
turkey 
