<TEXT>
field publications has settled charges that it 
mailed books to its subscribers that they had not asked for or 
agreed to receive and then billed them for payment the federal 
trade commission said monday 
field the publisher of weekly reader books and other book 
plans said it has acted to correct shortcomings of which the ftc 
had complained 
field spokeswoman pat sears said the company offers its book 
club members two or three opportunities a year to purchase 
quality materials and the ftc felt that we needed to do a 
better job of explaining how these programs work 
we agreed with them in september of 1989 we put into place a 
number of changes including some not requested by the ftc to 
assure that our customers would be properly served ms sears 
said from the companys office in middletown conn 
the ftc said the publishing company will pay civil penalties of 
175000 and will be prohibited in the future from the practices 
complained of under a consent decree filed in federal court 
a complaint acompanying the decree said field mailed additional 
books to subscribers who had consented to receive the companys 
regular subscription books it said the customers had not requested 
the shipment of the additional books or given express consent to 
having them mailed 
field then sent the customers invoices and dunned them for 
payment for the books the complaint said 
the ftc said this violates the unordered merchandise act a 
postal statute it prohibits the mailing of unordered merchandise 
except for free samples that are clearly and conspicuously marked 
it also prohibits the mailing or any bill or dunning notice to a 
recipient of unordered merchandise 
 
