<TEXT>
striking daily news columnist juan gonzalez 
doesnt object to being called a revolutionary long after he began 
to agitate on behalf of fellow puerto ricans as a youth 
when theres injustice you have to fight it he said i 
still consider myself a revolutionary if you mean someone who gets 
at the root of a problem in society and tries to correct it 
gonzalez a strike organizer for the newspaper guild was once a 
leader of the militant youth group young lords his past draws 
respect and a certain amount of amusement from his colleagues at 
the newspaper 
in the daily news library his photo file still says puerto 
rican revolutionary 
thats crossed out now it says daily news columnist 
said fellow striker robert gearty 
gonzalez file may or may not be changed again depending on the 
outcome of the strike by nine of 10 unions at the newspaper that 
has thrust him into the role of a strike leader 
one minute he is talking through a megaphone at a rally in 
front of the news building the next he is meeting with jesse 
jackson before a rally 
gonzalez colleagues on the picket line react energetically when 
he puts his hand on their shoulders to discuss how to produce the 
next union newsletter or strategy on the picket line 
gonzalez is cochairman of his unions strike organizing 
committee 
isnt juan amazing gearty said i saw him the other day 
i said juan where do i go to sign up for the young lords 
the young lords battled with authorities to push the cause of 
puerto rican independence and fair treatment of puerto ricans in 
the united states 
during the groups heyday from 1969 to 1974 gonzalez served as 
its minister of education and health and at one point as minister 
of defense 
they blocked major avenues in east harlem with garbage to 
protest poor trash collection they collected eggs bacon and bread 
from merchants and cooked breakfast for schoolchildren they staged 
sitins at a hospital and a church the latter leading to the 
arrest of 110 demonstrators 
at one point the group tried to replace police at the front of 
a parade leading police to attack the demonstrators and causing a 
major disturbance 
we got a little arrogant in our popularity gonzalez said 
we were blamed and rightly so for a raucous mess 
born in puerto rico 43 years ago gonzalez was raised in new 
york by a mother who was a garment worker and a father who labored 
in a restaurant both belonged to unions 
in 1968 gonzalez refused to accept his diploma from columbia 
university when the school asked him to plead guilty to violating 
university regulations for his role in a student strike that shut 
down the school for six weeks 
the same year he participated in protests at the democratic 
national convention in chicago 
gonzalez spent the next decade steam pressing mens suits at a 
garment factory and as a pressman at a printing plant because i 
was afraid if i became a professional i would become a sellout or a 
wimp 
he eventually gave in to his lifelong dream of writing for a 
newspaper by accepting a clerks position at the philadelphia daily 
news where he quickly became a reporter and helped organize a 
strike in 1985 
marnal whitley a striking librarian said when he first learned 
about gonzalezs past i thought maybe it was an ironic twist 
that maybe he had sold out 
but when i read his columns i saw he was still a 
revolutionary he is still on the side of the oppressed whitley 
said 
