<TEXT>
raymond oliver one of the greatest french chefs of 
the century and author of 26 books on cooking died monday after a 
long illness his family announced he was 81 
born at langon in the celebrated bordeaux food region in 1909 
oliver was the son and grandson of cooks his maternal grandmother 
gave him cooking lessons at an early age and he began his 
apprenticeship under his father at age 15 
in 1948 he purchased one of the great parisian restaurants le 
grand vefour and turned it into an exclusive dining spot for 
celebrities like politician andre malraux actor jean cocteau and 
writer colette 
oliver detested the light nouvelle cuisine popular in recent 
years his specialty was perfecting the rich cuisine of his 
bordeaux youth foie gras sauterne dove and caviar 
the important thing is design he once said to make good 
cuisine its necessary to have a solid base 
la vefour earned michelins prized third star five years after 
oliver bought it he ran it until his retirement at 75 following a 
terrorist bombing at the restaurant 
together with guy gerard jeanclaude vrinat and jacques 
maniere oliver was one of the most highly regarded chefs of his 
era he won several of frances top honors including officer of 
the legion of honor 
but his gift of communication elevated oliver above his 
contemporaries he was a prolific writer and from 1953 to 1968 
played host to the countrys most popular television food program 
art and magic from the kitchen 
a series of recorded recipes cuisinorama sold hundreds of 
thousands of copies and oliver defended french cuisine in lectures 
and seminars in the united states japan south africa and iceland 
he was married and had four children one of his sons 
established a chain of restaurants in french train stations his 
family did not disclose the cause of death and other details on 
survivors were not disclosed 
funeral arrangements were not announced 
</TEXT>
