<TEXT>
manufacturers would have to tell physicians 
how prescription drugs affect elderly patients under a government 
proposal announced monday 
the information some of which is already provided voluntarily 
by many companies already would have to be included in drug 
labeling sent to physicians and pharmacists said the food and drug 
administration this labeling required by the fda is usually 
available to patients upon request 
as our knowledge has grown of how drugs work within the body 
weve recognized the special concerns associated with drug use in 
the elderly health and human services secretary louis sullivan 
said in a statement 
physicians need to be provided with any patient information 
thats available about the drugs they prescribe for senior 
patients he said 
one of the differences between an old patient and a young one is 
the ability of their kidneys people lose a third or more of their 
kidney function between the ages of 30 and 90 sullivan said 
with less kidney function drugs do not clear the body as fast 
this might mean that a muscle relaxant that works fine for a young 
person might relax older people too much causing them to fall and 
break a hip he said 
the american association of retired persons said the proposal is 
important because those over 65 account for more than 30 percent of 
people taking prescription drugs while comprising 12 percent of the 
population 
one of the factors in drug misuse by the elderly is the 
amount of elderlyspecific information that comes from clinical 
trials and then goes to physicians to guide their prescribing 
practices said susan raetzman an aarp research analyst 
the proposal would require manufacturers to include in physician 
labeling all available information on the effects of the drug on 
the elderly this information could come from the clinical trials 
in which the drug was tested before it was approved for commercial 
sale or from medical literature said dr james mason assistant 
secretary for health at hhs 
if no information is available that would have to be stated 
clearly in the physician labeling but this would be the case 
primarily with drugs developed more than six years ago said dr 
robert temple director of the fdas office of drug evaluation i 
in the mid1980s the fda began requiring companies to include 
in drug applications any important data relating to the effects of 
the drug on the over65 population he said by 1988 most were 
doing it he said 
in march the fda issued guidelines to encourage drug companies 
to include the elderly when testing their products so they can pass 
on any effects of the drug in the elderly 
the labeling proposal could be made stronger if the fda made 
their guidelines for clinical trials mandatory aarps raetzman 
said as it is now their new labeling proposal is only as good 
as the information underlying it 
the fdas proposal would update the labeling regulation to 
standardize and make clear what information should be included 
the labeling information is also available in the physicians 
desk reference which provides information on all prescription 
drugs 
the fda said it will accept comments from the public for 60 
days after that a final rule will be drafted and published in the 
federal register 
drug manufacturers would have one year from the date of 
publication to comply updating the labeling of all their 
prescription products 
