<TEXT>
mount st helens belched volcanic ash 
and steam nearly 6 miles into the air monday and the powdery 
fallout settled up to 65 miles away in oregon 
there were no reports of damage and scientists said they had no 
evidence of a bigger eruption in the offing 
ashfall from the 8364foot mountain 100 miles south of seattle 
was reported as far away as the dalles ore 65 miles to the 
southeast said geologist steve brantley of the us geological 
survey 
residents of neighboring towns were not in any danger 
authorities said 
the explosion recorded on volcano seismographs at 207 am 
sent a plume of ash 30000 feet into the air said chris 
jonientztrisler a researcher at the university of washington 
winds carried the ash plume to the southeast toward the columbia 
river and into oregon the national weather service said 
jonientztrisler said the explosion was very minor minor 
minor compared with a may 18 1980 eruption that leveled 230 
square miles of forest left 57 people dead or missing and sent up 
an ash cloud that circled the globe 
this kind of thing is more like the steam and ash explosions 
that occurred last winter in december and january she said 
any hazards should be fairly confined to the crater 
scientists monitoring the volcano say there has been a gradual 
increase in small earthquakes there in the past three years there 
was no evidence however that they were associated with mondays 
eruption 
the steam and gases that are involved here could come from a 
couple of sources jonientztrisler said it could come from 
the magma bubbling out of solution or it could be rain and 
snowmelt percolating down to hot areas and bursting into steam 
its probably a bit of both processes 
in the past series of earthquakes have occurred in the days 
before eruptions of mount st helens 
the volcanos last large eruption was on march 19 1982 when 
mud flowed from the crater for six miles since then the mountain 
has had a series of domebuilding eruptions in which the 
mountain adds lava to the heap in its crater the last one occurred 
in october 1986 
the cataclysmic 1980 eruption blew off the top 1300 feet of the 
oncesymmetrical peak a lava dome dating to about the 16th 
century 
