<TEXT>
portauprince haiti ap tension mounted in haiti on monday 
the eve of a ruling on whether supporters of the duvalier 
dictatorship that terrorized the country for nearly three decades 
can run in the december elections 
the electoral council was expected tuesday to ban at least three 
duvalierists from participating and many haitians worried such a 
ruling could unleash a wave of violent retaliation as it did in 
1987 
november evokes for some a vision of apocalypse jean 
dominique director of the independent radio haitiinter said in a 
radio commentary in 1987 disqualified candidates put an already 
devastated country to the torch 
as night fell monday on the capital of portauprince where 
more than 1 million people live huge traffic jams formed as 
haitians stocked up on supplies and food in case of violence 
after the council barred 12 duvalierist candidates from the 1987 
race dozens of people were killed five radio stations were 
riddled with machinegun fire and put out of commission 
on election day goon squads in collusion with the army hacked 
and shot to death at least 34 voters at the polls the government 
then canceled the election 
this years elections are set for dec 16 the campaign 
officially begins wednesday and runs until dec 14 
the electoral council has constitutional authority to decide on 
the eligibility of the candidates the 1987 constitution bars 
architects of the duvalier dictatorship from running for 
office 
of this years 26 presidential candidates four are avowed 
duvalierists 
adding to tensions is the candidacy of the rev bertrand 
aristide an ardent foe of duvalierists and the military who has 
survived at least three assassination attempts 
many fear violent confrontations between duvalierists and his 
supporters a liberation theology advocate who believes the church 
should be involved in the social struggles of the poor aristide 
37 was ousted from his roman catholic salesian order in 1988 for 
allegedly inciting violence with his fiery sermons 
he is believed to have a mass following among haitis poor a 
majority in this caribbean nation of 6 million people 
the most feared duvalierist candidate is roger lafontant who 
ran the private tonton macoute militia that kept the duvalier 
family in power for 29 years 
the dictatorship ended in february 1986 when jeanclaude 
duvalier fled into exile but haiti has been wracked by political 
turmoil since he was toppled 
the current provisional government of ertha pascaltrouillot 
appointed in march is the fifth since duvalier fell 
there is a warrant for lafontants arrest charging him with 
conspiring against national security but it has not been served 
and hes thought to have military support lafontant returned to 
haiti in july after nearly five years in voluntary exile 
two other duvalierists candidates former army chief of staff 
claude raymond and clemard joseph charles a banker were barred 
from the 1987 elections 
remy joseph a doctor who was health minister under duvalier is 
regarded as a moderate and is expected to be allowed in the race 
about 800 observers from the united nations and organization of 
american states are expected to monitor the elections 
