<TEXT>
a federal judge refused to set bail monday for 
joseph doherty who for seven years has fought deportation for the 
1980 slaying of an army officer in northern ireland 
us district judge miriam g cedarbaum rejected dohertys 
request for bail saying he was likely to flee if released 
doherty 35 was arrested in new york in 1983 he faces a life 
sentence for the 1980 slaying of a british officer killed in a 
gunfight between british troops and dohertys fourman irish 
republican army unit 
doherty has never been charged with a crime in the united states 
and has been held without bail since his arrest he has said he 
quit the ira before coming to the united states in1982 
the evidence is overwhelming that petitioner if released 
would pose such a substantial risk of flight that no condition of 
bail could reasonably assure his surrender for deportation 
cedarbaum said in her decision 
doherty escaped from prison in northern ireland in 1981 and hid 
in this country with help from americans sympathetic to his cause 
she said 
while conceding that the length of detention was extremely 
troubling the judge rejected dohertys contention that his 
lengthy imprisonment violated his constitutional rights 
the judge said many constitutional protections did not apply to 
aliens in deportation proceedings 
dohertys lawyer mary pike said she would appeal the ruling 
there is something very ominous in the notion that an 
individual who is unconvicted of any crime can be imprisoned for in 
excess of seven years pike said 
the irishamerican community has rallied around doherty naming 
him honorary grand marshal of st patricks day parades around the 
country and sending him thousands of letters of support 
dozens of politicians and religious leaders have visited him in 
prison the city also gave his name to a street near the facility 
