democrats filed a complaint monday with the 
federal election commission alleging that a group headed by 
evangelist pat robertson had failed to report spending against 
democratic house candidates in four states 
robertson rejected the suggestion that the group has failed to 
meet federal requirements 
the complaint alleged that robertsons christian coalition has 
been buying radio spots and sending mail opposing democratic 
candidates in at least four house districts criticizing and 
often distorting their voting records 
the documents filed by the democratic congressional campaign 
committee named incumbent reps ben jones of georgia pat williams 
of montana richard stallings of idaho and jolene unsoeld of 
washington unsoeld and jones both freshmen are locked in 
cliffhanger reelection races 
in a radio spot aimed at williams the group contends that the 
lawmaker wants to raise our taxes to pay for pornography 
williams has been a prominent defender of the national endowment 
for the arts against attacks by conservatives who say it funds 
obscene art 
letters addressed dear christian friend went into jones 
district making similar allegations and asking for money for the 
christian coalition 
organizations which spend money to promote or defeat candidates 
on their own without coordinating with the candidates own 
campaigns are allowed unlimited spending but must register with 
the fec and report their activities and the sources of their money 
the group has failed to do so the dccc charged 
the coalition isnt urging the defeat or election of any 
candidate and the radio spots constitute a public education 
campaign said frankie abourjilie a spokeswoman for robertson the 
spots suggest that listeners write the candidates and tell them how 
they feel about the issues 
it is incredible that some members of congress dont want to 
face voters on critical issues such as taxes and how those tax 
dollars are spent robertson said in a statement through 
abourjilie 
our interest is in securing votes against taxfunded 
pornography the coalitions executive director ralph reed said 
last week 
the christian coalition was formed as a nonprofit evangelical 
organization by robertson a religious broadcaster and 1988 
republican presidential candidate its literature says it is not 
affiliated with any political party and doesnt endorse candidates 
but coalition director ralph reed in a nov 1 appearance on 
robertsons 700 club television program said the group was 
distributing voter guides in hopes of increasing turnout and 
