<TEXT>
pulitzer prizewinning reporter hg bissinger 
went to a small texas town to discover how high school sports can 
bind a community 
what he found was a town where racism was rampant football 
received more support than english and school district lines were 
drawn to make sure that the best athletes went to the best school 
friday night lights a town a team and a dream has become 
a best seller but not in odessa where threats were made to two 
bookstores carrying the volume the author said 
bissinger gives a graphic look inside the permian high school 
huddle and field house and into the friday night spectacle of 
packed stadiums and screaming fans 
i went in search of the friday night lights to find a town 
where they brightly blazed that lay beyond the east coast and the 
grip of the big cities a place that people had to pull out an 
atlas to find and had seen better times a real america writes 
bissinger who won a pulitzer prize in 1987 with two other 
philadelphia inquirer reporters for a sixpart investigative series 
exposing corruption in the philadelphia court system he now works 
for the chicago tribune 
bissinger said he found those lights in odessa and they burned 
with more intensity than he had ever imagined 
like thousands of others i got caught up in them he said 
so did my wife so did my children as someone later described 
it those lights become an addiction if you live in a place like 
odessa the friday night fix 
he was troubled by how many people in odessa traced the citys 
troubles to a judges desegregation order in 1982 the order forced 
the closing of odessas predominantly black ector high school and 
divided its students between permian and odessa high schools with 
district lines suspiciously drawn so the top black athletes would 
go to permian 
bissinger said he found common use of the word nigger among 
boosters public officials merchants and ordinary residents as 
well as coaches and white players on permians predominantly white 
football team the panthers 
permians coaches were openly derisive of blacks when none was 
around and forced players to compete when injured the author said 
shots were given at halftime of games to relieve pain or to replace 
body fluids 
i was extremely disappointed there were so many things he 
could have written that were positive that werent focused on 
said thencoach gary gaines who gave bissinger unrestricted access 
to permian during 1988 when the twicebeaten panthers lost again in 
the state semifinals 
we just gave him free run of the mill said gaines now 
defensive secondary coach at texas tech he came and went and 
attended every practice every game every meeting he was writing 
all the time we didnt have anything to hide we really liked the 
guy 
what stings the most gaines said is the books portrayal of 
him and his coaches as racists 
that hurts because that certainly is not what we based our 
program on he said we dont talk like that and didnt 
gaines said he took bissinger at his word that he planned to 
write a positive book about the fabled odessa permian football 
program 
bissinger however said he doesnt recall telling gaines he was 
doing a positive piece 
i think i told him there were elements that would be positive 
and i felt that the book would have been positive the author 
said but a lot of things happened that made it impossible to be 
a positive book im not the one who called an 18yearold 
black kid a big old dumb nigger one of his coaches did that i 
certainly wasnt the one who sent the wrong film to harvard on 
behalf of a black kid a game in which the student didnt play 
that was coach gaines 
i knew these people and became friendly with them and it was 
difficult to write the things i did but i had to be honest and 
objective and say things i felt had to be said 
bissinger was spurred into writing the book in part because of 
his own past as an addicted sports fan who had spent much of 
his time watching football basketball and baseball 
the idea had been rattling in my head since i was 13 years 
old the idea of high school sports keeping a town together 
keeping it alive he said 
bissinger played two years of high school football and was 
sports editor of both his high school and college newspaper the 
daily pennsylvanian at university of pennsylvania 
friday night lights describes a city hit hard when oil 
prices plummeted in the early 1980s ruining a region that depends 
upon petroleum 
odessas obsession with one of the nations most successful high 
school football programs enabled residents to keep their heads high 
and remain upbeat no matter how bleak the economy the panthers 
have been in nine state finals since 1965 winning five 
championships three in the 80s 
but to its detriment odessa relegated everything else behind 
football bissinger writes 
little was expected academically of permian football players 
the book says one linemans senior year classes consisted of 
government and the electives of sociology computer math 
photography and food science 
he breezed through them with ease then came the hard work he 
got to football practice where the demands and pressures were 
ceaseless the second he stepped on the field bissinger wrote 
nothing he did went unnoticed if he did something well he 
received praise if he did something wrong it was pointed out in 
painstaking detail and if it wasnt detected during practice it 
was discovered afterward when the coaches retired to their office 
to watch videos of the days workout on the elaborate video machine 
that had been donated by the booster club 
during the 1988 season permian spent 70000 for chartered jets 
for the players to and from distant game sites 
the school spent more for medical supplies for athletic programs 
at permian 6750 than it did for teaching materials for the 
english department 5040 which did not cover required 
textbooks 
the salary of the head of the english department at permian was 
32000 compared to gaines salary of 48000 plus free use of a 
new sedan each year 
