screenwriter bruce joel rubin recently talked 
about how to turn nighttime dreams into fun and profit 
jacobs ladder came to me as a dream he said it 
started with me in the subway the underworld of new york in a 
sense as i left the train and walked along a very deserted 
platform late at night i walked up the stairs and found the gate 
was locked that has happened to me in real life but in the dream 
i just felt that something was wrong 
i walked to the other end of the platform and that exit was 
locked as well i got very frightened and i said something 
terrible is happening i had this feeling that the only way out 
was down through the bowels of new york i felt i would have to go 
to hell to become free to get out 
thats the start of tim robbins descent into a personal hell in 
jacobs ladder its a thriller written by rubin a hot 
screenwriter because of ghost and directed by adrian lyne 
also hot because of fatal attraction 
robbins is a vietnam veteran beset with dreams and 
hallucinations he learns that his combat buddies have undergone 
the same bedevilment and he tries to discover the reason 
two years have passed since lynes sensationridden fatal 
attraction why the gap the director explained that jacobs 
ladder started at paramount pictures but fell from favor after a 
change in regimes the project shifted to columbia pictures 
also i worked for a year on the special effects aspects of 
the movie he added one problem that took a long while was 
that we did all the special effects incamera when we shot rather 
than handing over the special effects as a kind of package to a 
company like ilm industrial light and magic 
i was anxious to do it that way because i think that sometimes 
movies with special effects get into a kind of sameness because 
the same guy is doing the special effects for all of them 
robbins known for his offcenter comedy in such movies as 
bull durham and cadillac man was a surprise casting as the 
bedeviled veteran 
he obviously wasnt an obvious choice in commercial terms 
lyne admitted the studio would have been happy with a mel gibson 
or a harrison ford who bring an audience to a movie i liked tim 
i think hes a very vulnerable sympathetic man for a start and i 
loved him in bull durham 
because this is a kind of dark story i thought it was 
important to have an actor who had a sense of humor tim is an 
actor who finds humor where it doesnt necessarily exist in a 
scene 
lyne who also directed flashdance and 9 weeks now has 
made two thrillers in a row how far can he go with terror 
i think if its kind of gratuitous if youre just doing it 
for effect the audience senses it and it doesnt work he said 
i learned an awful lot from making fatal attraction i studied 
a lot of suspense movies and hopefully i learned from them i 
think there are moments in jacobs ladder that are genuinely 
frightening 
when i see a movie i like to be put through it i like having 
highs up there and lows down there and feeling drained at the end 
of the movie as though id been through something thats better 
than a movie that just washes over you and is forgotten in two 
minutes 
bruce joel rubin will turn directorwriter on his next project 
for paramount 
one of the wonderful benefits of being a successful writer in 
hollywood is that they allow you to do what i consider to be 
writing the final draft of a movie that is to direct it he 
said screenplays in hollywood are never really seen by anybody 
but the director and some studio people what is on the screen is 
the ultimate screenplay its not what the writer wrote 
its very frustrating for a writer to have his work translated 
by other people im the luckiest guy alive to have had wonderful 
translations what ive wanted more than anything is to direct my 
own scripts now thanks to the success of ghost paramount has 
given me that opportunity 
