<TEXT>
historian marvin olasky looked at how american 
society took care of its wretched poor 100 years ago and how it 
does it now and concludes people did it better then 
charity in the 1890s he said was not left to the welfare and 
charitable bureaucracies compassion was not dispensed with a 
checkbook 
instead he said helping the poor involved ordinary working 
people not much better off than those they helped they took the 
needy into their homes or into church basements and showed them 
the door if they refused to lift a hand on their own behalf 
in a word charity involved compassion he said an element that 
is lost when helping the poor is left to institutions 
olasky a university of texas professor of journalism history 
is on leave as a scholar in residence at an antiabortion group 
the americans united for life legal defense fund 
he is writing a book on the role of compassion and spent a year 
at the library of congress digging into newspapers and magazines 
studying how paupers were treated a century ago 
then for contrast he spent a few days walking around 
washington posing as a homeless person in shelters he said he 
got plenty to eat but no one ever suggested that he do anything for 
himself at one shelter he said he asked for a bible and got a 
stare instead 
in an article in policy review quarterly magazine of the 
heritage foundation a conservative research organization olasky 
asks whether society is better off now than it was when charity was 
a function of individual responsibility he concludes that then was 
better than now 
but robert bothwell executive director of the national 
committee for responsive philanthropy a nonprofit organization 
that monitors the world of charity has some doubts our 
industrialized society he said has eliminated many jobs formerly 
done by the unskilled poor 
olaskys thesis is that the way the poor are helped now is 
expedient but ultimately unhelpful 
the major flaw of the modern welfare state is not that it is 
extravagant but that it is too stingy he writes it gives the 
needy bread and tells them to be content with that alone it gives 
the rest of us the opportunity to be stingy also and to salve our 
consciences even as we scrimp on what many of the destitute need 
most love time and a challenge to be little lower than the 
angels rather than one thumb up from monkeys 
but most significantly he said a century ago people made 
moral demands on recipients of aid they did not allow anyone 
to eat and run 
a century ago olasky writes charitable people often poor 
themselves provided food shelter work organized excursions and 
summer camps staffed dispensaries and ran schools missions and 
reading rooms 
new york city alone had 1288 charitable organizations many 
looked after members of their own nationality group 
firstgeneration italians took care of newly arrived immigrants 
from the homeland the same was true of swedes irish russians 
some charities had remarkably nononsense names such as the 
erring womans refuge or the union for homeless and friendless 
girls 
women volunteers worked by day men by night 
these principles olasky said prevailed 
before someone received a handout an effort was made to find 
family members who could care for him 
longterm oneonone contacts were forged between the volunteer 
and the needy person 
charity went only to those worthy of relief those poor 
through no fault of their own and unable to change that situation 
quickly the aged ill and children the shiftless and 
intemperate were classified not entitled to relief and shown 
the door before a man got a meal he was asked to spend two hours 
chopping wood a needy woman was shown to the sewing room 
woodyards next to homeless shelters were as common in 1890 
said olasky as liquor stores are in 1990 
relief was given only after investigation benign suspicion 
was applied to those seeking aid 
freedom from dependency was crucial the goal of charity 
workers said olasky was to show poor people how to move up 
while resisting enslavement to the charity of governmental or 
private masters 
charity had religious underpinnings groups such as the 
industrial christian alliance didnt hesitate to remind the poor 
that god made them and had high expectations for them 
in an interview olasky spelled out his conclusions it all 
comes down to your understanding of what compassion is mutual 
obligation was essential the person who was better off was 
obligated to suffer with not just write a check or pass a law 
and the person who needed help was obligated to change 
now if your definition of compassion is merely the provision 
of material help then youre not going to like my suggestions 
bothwell of the national committee for responsive philanthropy 
is somewhat skeptical he welcomes olaskys holistic remedy 
charity should treat the whole person not just a segment of the 
problem but makes the point that society has changed in 
fundamental ways 
in 19th century cities sweatshops provided jobs for unskilled 
immigrants the gap between workers and nonworkers was not great 
and an unemployed person could easily move into the ranks of the 
respectfully employed by taking such a job 
todays counterpart job bothwell notes might be flipping 
burgers in a fast food restaurant but that kind of work doesnt 
pay enough to lift a family from poverty 
it is true bothwell said that society in this era of busy 
lives and twoincome families largely has turned over to 
government the responsibility of providing a safety net but he 
said olasky overlooks the enormous amount of private help that 
still exists in a country with more than 800000 nonprofit 
organizations 
moreover todays immigrants now likely to come from the 
soviet union east europe latin america or asia still find 
nationality groups to give them a lift newcomers still move in 
with those who proceeded them 
everybody knows that weve grown into a society that is much 
more distant than the world olasky describes bothwell said so 
you devise different ways of assisting people and one of them is 
the more distant more automatic way of providing money to the 
destitute through the governments safety net 
</TEXT>
