failed and officials now grope for ways to promote cultural 
integration 
the immigrant question shares the political agenda with the 
new europe an interloper of another sort 
france has been a driving force toward unity challenging the 
european community to go beyond the open frontiers of 1992 toward 
political union 
but the bravado masks worries that are particularly french how 
to remain rigorously independent in an interdependent community of 
nations and retain the national identity that is it often seems 
frances raison detre 
france currently is facing its most profound identity crisis 
since the advent of the fifth republic in 1958 according to 
gregory flynn a european affairs specialist with the carnegie 
endowment for international peace in washington 
the french he wrote in the wall street journal fear for 
identity more than security and worry about losing all traces of 
their status as a world power 
france appears wellplaced to assume a leadership role in a 
united europe but questions arise about its willingness to 
suppress its nationalistic instincts 
everything is happening as though the french no longer able 
to change the world or protect themselves from it persuaded 
themselves that as a nation they can do nothing at all says the 
governmentordered report on the state of the nation 
the french have long sought to protect their national identity 
politically and culturally the report says from now on they 
will have to choose other criteria for success 
many experts are optimistic 
todd a member of the government panel says france has far more 
confidence now than a few decades ago when the folly of grandeur 
a perverse national obsession bolstered a humiliated nation 
france is one of the european countries changing most 
quickly todd says so its normal that some people have 
doubts nostalgia dream of a peaceful and tranquil france 
crozier says you dont redefine what is french its not an 
intellectual operation its something that just happens 
