editors note the torch is being passed in singapore the 
former british colony that has become one of asias most prosperous 
nations under the authoritarian rule of lee kuan yew after more 
than three decades lee on nov 28 will relinquish his post as 
prime minister to goh chok tong who like george bush is 
promising a kinder and gentler country 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in his 31 years as prime minister of singapore 
lee kuan yew ruled as a nononsense stern taskmaster 
we decide what is right he once said never mind what the 
people think 
there were no free lunches fun and games had to have a purpose 
and hopefully show a profit 
now that lee is stepping down his successor says that the time 
has come to lighten up 
first deputy prime minister goh chok tong is scheduled to take 
over on nov 28 he says he plans no radical change but will scrap 
the paternalistic approach and loosen the reins of government 
the society which we want to bring about will be more refined 
more compassionate kinder and gentler goh promised 
under lee the former british colony of singapore began its 
existence as an independent citystate with a weak economy no 
industry unfriendly neighbors and bitter racial divisions among 
chinese malays and indians 
today singapore with 27 million people is one of asias most 
prosperous nations 
described as authoritarian even by his admirers lee offers no 
apologies for his hardnosed methods 
no leader can be a softy and hope to survive the worlds 
longestserving elected government head told university students 
recently 
the largest single difference in style between goh chok tong 
and me will not be because of differences in temperament or 
character but because of his commitment to team leadership he 
consults all key parties affected before he takes major 
decisions 
lee said several years ago that his political heirs sometimes 
did not seem tough enough to handle the opposition and other 
critics have they got enough people with that fire in the belly 
and iron in the soul 
goh has a quick brain and is decisive but tries to please too 
many people lee said with typical bluntness 
lee nevertheless planned an orderly transition of power to a new 
generation but he admitted publicly in 1988 that he preferred 
education minister tony tan instead of the amiable goh as his 
successor tan did not aspire to the role 
while relinquishing the prime ministers title lee 67 expects 
to remain politically active he will serve in gohs cabinet as 
senior minister without portfolio and continue as chairman of the 
ruling peoples action party 
it is to singapores advantage that he should remain as a 
factor in our domestic politics and even in our foreign 
relations goh said 
as the elected head of the peoples action party lee became 
prime minister and controlled who was named to cabinet positions 
he also had the power to choose his successor 
under the constitution elections are held at intervals not to 
exceed five years 
the constitution is being amended to elect and give executive 
powers to the nowceremonial and appointed presidency lee 
suggested the change in 1984 to help safeguard the countrys vast 
financial reserves 
he has not ruled out the possibility that he might seek the 
revamped post after president wee kim wee retires 
the lee factor in singapore politics was also reflected by gohs 
appointment of lee hsien loong 38 the prime ministers eldest 
son as one of two deputy prime ministers in the new government 
the appointment came as no surprise goh earlier acknowledged 
that the younger lee was his logical successor as prime minister 
but goh 49 insists that he will not serve in a transitional role 
to keep the seat warm for the ambitious lee 
there is no such arrangement goh says 
lee hsien loong is the cabinet member in charge of trade and 
industry he entered politics in 1984 after a 13year army career 
in which he moved through the ranks from cadet to brigadier 
general 
there will be life after lee kuan yew because we have a team 
of men who are just as determined as lee kuan yew was when he 
started building singapore goh says 
against heavy odds lee turned an unpromising relic of the 
british empire into a glittering commercial success and test tube 
for social change 
fortunately for us when we set out to organize ourselves in 
the 1960s we did not believe in pie in the sky lee told a 
recent gathering in his tanjong pagar constituency we went in 
for equality of opportunity but not equal pay that made everybody 
do their best 
the cambridgeeducated lawyer took charge in 1959 when the 
colony gained limited selfrule it joined the new malaysian 
federation in 1963 only to be expelled two years later because lee 
and other chinese leaders were seen as a threat to the political 
control of indigenous malays 
</TEXT>
