<TEXT>
other voices columbia paul young 
paul young says other voices his first album in two years 
represents a change in musical direction but its hard to hear 
much difference between the best material on this album and youngs 
bestknown songs from the past including his huge 1985 hit 
everytime you go away 
youngs strength is his passionate way with a soul tune hes in 
fine form here with a tasty cover of the 20yearold chilites hit 
oh girl and a muscular production of peter wolfs its what 
she didnt say a song cowritten by young 
one wonders though why young doesnt stick with what he does 
best instead other voices is a grab bag of styles with a 
different producer on almost every track 
it also features a long roster of guest artists chaka kahn 
david gilmour steve winwood peter wolf and stevie wonder among 
others 
but the guest stars hardly shine and this likeable album would 
have been better with a bigger dose of soul 
by david dishneau associated press writer 
 
 
 
french eelodies emi jose van dam baritone jeanphilippe 
collard piano 
songs piano works by reynaldo hahn ades jeanchristophe 
benoit baritone bernard ringeissen piano 
 
italy in the 19thcentury never really answered the german lied 
preferring to let its voices excel in opera the french with their 
melodies did a better job 
two recent cd releases in very different ways give a taste of 
a form that began with berlioz gloried in debussy ravel and faure 
and continued through les six that rebellious collection of french 
composers after world war i which included poulenc 
hahn 18751947 a now obscure frenchman of venezuelan descent 
wrote operas operettas and ballets and conducted in the theater 
during his maturity but his guarantee against oblivion are songs 
written when hahn was a teenager and in his early 20s 
benoit offers 19 of them around a fivepiece piano solo 
interlude they are plenty charming in the best parisian salon 
sense but frequently hahn rises above that with some truly 
beautiful writing its hard to resist them 
benoits voice has an open appropriate drawingroom quality 
but it wavers and sounds a little unsteady his pitch sometimes has 
the same problem but the performances are genuine and 
affectionate the recorded sound has immediacy and rengeissen is 
always sensitive ten demerits to ades for providing no text 
of a wholly different vocal order is van dam his voice has a 
beautiful rich quality in which the vibration is a natural 
outgrowth of the core of his sound a quality which benoit lacks 
van dam brings strong characterizations to this varied survey 
which includes songs by berlioz his famous les nuits dete 
ibert faure poulenc and ropartz 
van dam defines dynamic control producing tightly reined 
crescendos and diminuendos the highlights are the ibert songs on 
poems about don quixote who van dam portrays with a melancholy 
nobility and poulencs baudy chansons gaillardes based on 
anonymous 17thcentury texts of a rabelaisian flavor the program 
is well put together the wideeyed piety of faures at prayer 
immediately precedes the first poulenc number about a fickle 
mistress and her virginity collard is exceedingly elegant 
throughout text and translation provided 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
