<TEXT>
a holiday dessert thats traditional but still different to 
american palates is the kransekage from denmark 
this rich but light sweet is simple and quick to make and is put 
together in a way that will let you use your creativity stack the 
rings to make a christmas tree lay them out into a cornucopia or 
whatever your imagination suggests the danes adapt it for many 
special occasions often serving it with brandy 
this recipe comes from from conditori la glace in copenhagen 
one of denmarks bestknown coffee and cake houses proprietor 
marianne stagetorn and her chief confectioner ebbe jepsen offer 
it along with dozens of layer cakes and confections many named 
after royalty or famous people at the shop which has been at the 
same skoubogade 3 address in copenhagen for 120 years another 
shop opened last year on kongens nytorv also in the heart of the 
city its not anything like the heavy stickybun danish pastries 
found in american coffee shops 
 
kransekage 
 
2 pounds 3 ounces marzipan 
2 cups sugar 
23 cup egg whites 
white icing 
 
blend marzipan and sugar well then add egg whites mix well 
form into 14 rings in ascending cigarshaped sizes the largest 
ring should measure approximately 8 inches in diameter and the 
smallest 2 inches in diameter bake 7 minutes in a 475degree 
oven 
decorate with white icing piping thin swirls onto each ring 
use icing to secure the rings stacking them into an inverted cone 
shape trim with colored decorations mounted on picks la glace 
shows it with small paper danish flags this will make 25 
servings 
</TEXT>
