<TEXT>
british telecommunication plc and mci 
communications corp have agreed to build a 400 million 
transatlantic fiber optic cable to relieve a telecommunication 
capacity shortage mci said today 
the two companies are inviting other international 
telecommunications carriers to participate in the planning 
construction and operation of the new highcapacity cable expected 
to be the largest undersea telecommunication line ever constructed 
the companies will share the cost of construction according to 
their percentage of ownership mci spokesman david thompson said 
this is the first time that mci initiated the planning of a 
transatlantic cable that will be built operated and owned by a 
consortium of common carriers mci president bert c roberts jr 
said in a written statement 
it is a step toward providing an integrated network of 
mutually supportive cables across the north atlantic he said 
mci said it would handle the equivalent of 150000 simultaneous 
phone calls the first transatlantic cable completed in 1956 
could handle only 60 simultaneous calls thompson said 
the cable currently called tatx is scheduled to go into 
service in 1993 it will be the seventh such cable in operation 
after the construction of tat9 is completed in 1991 thompson 
said 
the companies plan to use the line with synchronous optical 
transmission equipment which is designed to allow centralized 
control of circuits maintenance testing and cable restoration 
tatx also will provide service for other cables in case of 
service interruptions 
</TEXT>
