<TEXT>
the leading airline industry group on monday 
recommended up to an 8 percent increase in passenger fares and 7 
percent rise in cargo prices to help airlines offset high fuel 
costs caused by the persian gulf crisis 
the international air transport associations recommendations 
issued during its conference in geneva marked the second time 
since the crisis began three months ago that the airline industry 
has moved to raise prices because of fuel inflation any increase 
is subject to approval by affected countries 
the airlines want the increases to take effect by middecember 
but association officials said some governments might not address 
the question until after the christmas holidays 
airline industry profits have been battered by slowing economies 
in the united states and elsewhere the rising cost of jet fuel 
since iraq seized kuwait three months ago has made matters worse 
for many carriers who must buy enormous quantities of fuel at 
prices that fluctuate daily 
the association said in a statement the increase in prices to 
customers are to recover at least partially continued cost 
increases particularly in fuel prices 
in august airlines in the association said they would initially 
boost international passenger fares by 8 percent 
unlike fares in the united states which have been deregulated 
since 1978 most international fares are determined by agreement 
among airlines and national governments 
industry officials say the previous fare increase which 
generally took effect this month failed to cover higher costs 
caused by the jump in oil prices seesawing crudeoil prices in 
recent weeks have added to the financial strain 
the international air transport association is the industrys 
leading group with about 200 member airlines 
