<TEXT>
ibm northern telecom inc and nynex corp on 
monday announced a product that links incoming phone calls at a 
company or organization with computerized information on the 
caller 
the system will make it easier for example for customer 
service representatives at a mailorder house to handle inquiries 
and for publicsafety officials at a college to locate a caller in 
an emergency the companies said 
previously such systems only were available to companies owning 
expensive inhouse phone switching systems 
the new system is aimed at companies and organizations that do 
not have their own private phone system it operates through the 
electronic centraloffice switch of the local phone company 
the systems match the number of an incoming phone call with a 
computer file the file then pops up on a screen using the same 
telephone network technology as residential caller id systems 
that flash the number of an incoming call on a small screen near 
the telephone 
for instance a customers file would appear on a screen at a 
mail order catalog company where that customers has an account 
before the customer service representative even picks up the phone 
syracuse university will become the first phone user to 
participate in a demonstration of the new system which is called 
compucall by northern telecom a canadianbased maker of phone 
company switching gear 
with the system the colleges inhouse emergency phone number 
will be linked to computerized files on the location of every phone 
on campus and nearby emergency exits the information for the 
particular phone will show up on a computer screen as the call is 
answered 
like the caller id system the new phone technology could raise 
concerns about callers privacy caller id systems have been 
criticized because they provide a callers phone number which can 
be used without permission for marketing or other purposes 
american telephone amp telegraph co northern telecoms principal 
north american rival in central phone switches does not offer a 
similar system said joe bellace a merrill lynch amp co analyst 
however he called the system a future product that should 
not have significant earnings impact for the three participating 
companies for some time 
northern telecom said the system only works with international 
business machines corp minicomputers but eventually should be 
expanded to other makes 
ibm earlier this year announced a system called callpath that 
links its minicomputers with incoming phone calls over private 
phone systems made by several companies 
</TEXT>
