<TEXT>
the market for socalled multimedia computing 
got a boost monday as intel corp announced new chips that should 
cut the cost of adding video technology to personal computers 
intel says its chips should allow computer makers to offer 
machines that edit and store moving images much like they do text 
for about 1000 more than a regular computer 
while similar technology exists it costs at least 2000 above 
the price of a personal computer intel said 
intel said its technology should spur the growth of multimedia 
or the marriage of television and computing multimedia which has 
yet to take off allows the data text and interactive capabilities 
of computers to be mixed with video stereo sound still 
photographs and animation 
multimedia already is used fornd zeros of 
computer language intels chips for example compress video data 
by a factor of at least 100 to 1 
the images then can be stored on a computers internal hard disk 
or for greater capacity on a compact disk similar to those used 
in home audio systems 
intel says its system is the only one designed for ordinary ibm 
personal computers and compatible models competing systems require 
specialized more costly computers said intel spokeswoman karen 
andring 
intel said its technology also is superior to systems using 
video disk players to incorporate video into computer programs 
since these systems do not convert the video into digital form it 
cannot be manipulated on the computer screen in addition intel 
says its system is cheaper 
with intels system a computer user could connect a vcr to a 
desktop machine and insert sections of a television program or 
movie into a computer program the system allows special video 
effects such as fading zooming and panning 
intels technology originally was developed at the david sarnoff 
research center in princeton nj intel bought the technology from 
general electric co in 1988 and since has been developing it in 
conjunction with ibm 
the technology which intel calls dvi for digital video 
interactive originally took up seven computer boards and cost 
about 22000 in february intel made the same system available on 
two computer boards for 2000 
at a demonstration monday in new york intel announced it had 
shrunk much of the technology to fit onto two fingernailsized 
computer chips for under 100 further enhancements should make the 
chips even more powerful and cheaper intel said 
however the chips only provide the heart of the system so 
other components are needed to actually incorporate mulitimedia 
into computers boosting the price to the expected 1000 level 
among computer and software makers exploring intels technology 
or already offering it are american telephone amp telegraph co 
compaq computer corp microsoft corp lotus development corp 
olivetti of italy and toshiba aiwa and matsushita of japan intel 
said 
in addition picturetel corp a maker of video phones is 
collaborating with intel in research that could slash the price of 
video phones and make the technology common on personal computers 
said norman gaut picturetels chairman 
</TEXT>
