<TEXT>
european community agriculture and 
trade ministers late monday suspended talks on a proposal to cut 
farm subsidies until tuesday morning to give time for highlevel 
consultations between ec governments 
officials said several ec heads of state including french 
president francois mitterrand and german chancellor helmut kohl 
were talkin by phone in attempts to arrange a final farm plan 
an ec official who asked not to be named said negotiators were 
treating the tuesday meeting as an unofficial deadline for an 
agreement 
the ministers are working under the threat that failure to reach 
agreement soon could torpedo talks to liberalize world trade 
the issue of farm subsidies is one of the key obstacles to the 
broader trade negotiations the united states and other 
agricultural exporters contend the ec unfairly subsidizes farmers 
enabling them to sell food more cheaply abroad 
officials said italian trade minister renato ruggiero told the 
ministers during mondays meeting that it was crucial they 
agree on cutting subsidies for farmers 
if not the united states would use the ecs failure to do so as 
a reason to abandon the uruguay round talks a fouryear effort of 
more than 100 nations to liberalize world trade the officials 
quoted ruggiero as saying 
those talks are due to end in december 
british agriculture secretary john gummer said if we dont 
find a solution now we will look ridiculous 
the ministers were at odds over a proposal to trim farm 
subsidies on major crops by 30 percent over a period of years 
france and germany have been insisting on guarantees that the 
trims would not seriously hurt their farmers in preparation for 
mondays meeting the european commission the communitys 
executive body devised a list of guarantees designed to allay the 
nations fears but it was not clear whether it would succeed 
logically there ought to be no reason why we cant come to an 
agreement said gummer 
but another community official said i dont see any change i 
dont see any movement the ministers were repeating the same 
position they have held for a month the official said 
france the communitys largest exporter of farm products still 
appeared to have doubts 
ministers from the 12 ec nations failed in six tries last month 
to reach an accord 
ruggiero opened mondays session saying the offer of a 30 
percent cut in subsidies is not minimal but of great value 
