local and national labor leaders pledged 2 
million monday to help the unions striking the daily news while 
management fought to get the newspaper to readers 
the tabloid has continued to publish since the strike began 
nearly two weeks ago with editors joined by reporters and editors 
from other newspapers union members who have crossed the picket 
line and new hires 
but with editorial and production problems apparently licked the 
job of getting the paper to wouldbe readers remained 
eight unions struck on oct 25 followed the next day by the 
newspaper guild which represents reporters photographers and 
other workers about 2000 people are on strike although some have 
returned in various guild departments 
the unions went on strike over what they termed unfair labor 
practices they had been involved in negotiations since january 
over contracts that expired in march 
the printers stayed on the job to preserve lifetime job 
guarantees negotiated when automation was introduced 
nine other unions representing groups from teamsters to teachers 
agreed monday to cosign a 2 million loan to assist the strikers 
we were very delighted to hear this morning that they were 
going to help us reach a strike fund of 2 million said george 
mcdonald president of the allied printing trades council a 
coalition of 10 unions at the news 
we need it to go out on radio and tv and fight the enemy he 
said 
news spokeswoman lisa robinson has declined to provide printing 
and circulation figures since friday figures provided by the news 
have been widely disputed 
however robinson did say the news has had tremendous success 
getting the paper out hawkers are giving away free papers 
including 50000 on sunday more are to be placed in regional 
malls but she would not disclose where 
were moving toward our normal routine circulation she 
said the news circulation is 109 million on weekdays and 14 
million on sundays it is the third largest metropolitan daily in 
the country 
